On Fri, 16 Apr 2004, Chris M. wrote:

> I swapped my speedo in my Mustang
>and wanted the mileage on the newer ODO to match the mileage on the old
>ODO. Hooked up a drill and ran it full speed and it said 35 mph. Uh no.
>This is going to take a month. So I learned to disassemble the ODO and
>fixed it all up in 20 minutes or so. I can see why all the used car
>dealers have goten in trouble over the years. Too easy to do the mileage
>change, and too easy to see evidence of the tools required.

Not really true of buses.  You can disassemble the odo without leaving
any tool marks.  The only permenent marks you make are on the odometer
shaft as you dremel off the flats that hold it in place.

